1Gt7aQzaTbMdMp-XOoozIq3fUC5tfz8rdIB0b\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating test dependencies**\\n\\nI’m looking into the `nativeTest`, which might run a standard test before the native one. After passing the JVM, the native run could fail. The task requests active GWTTestAccessor only, while the existing tests seem irrelevant. Disabling those tests could be an option, but we shouldn't skip the native run.\\n\\nIt looks like the user's error stems from our previous dependency choice. I need to inspect whether we should run tests at all or just check the dependencies. The GWT compiler shows a duplicate validation-api source, so I wonder about package group allowances and metadata.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering native image builds**\\n\\nBuilding a native image for tests might need Hibernate Validator classes. If there are no resources in native, the ServiceLoader could fail at runtime due to no provider being available. I wonder if I could use `Validation.byProvider(HibernateValidator.class)` directly to avoid that, but the GWT source contains `BeanHelperCache`, which uses `Validation.buildDefaultValidatorFactory()`, and I can’t change that. \\n\\nIs it possible that the native build includes the provider? I think GraalVM typically auto-detects ServiceLoader, and native images usually include services by default.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_fW3Y50Kv8J0tVSLzccMYAqo2|fc_0daccf359b7d25be0169f565839b5881a3848044bd6d95ffea", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.gwtproject/gwt-user/2.11.0/build.gradle"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 918, "output": 832, "cacheRead": 53760, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 55510, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777689973781, "responseId": "resp_0daccf359b7d25be0169f565766e1c81a391c45f82c2957e83"}}
